From 5c088ba94830d45982575f0fc91ee61f26f7615c Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Claude <claude@anthropic.com>
Date: Fri, 17 Jul 2026 02:15:56 +0000
Subject: [PATCH] Step 1 of the workflow-configurability plan: change-impact
 warnings

Before this, editing a process definition's requiresChecklist/
requiresVerification/isActive (or any field) took effect instantly for
every task currently referencing it - ProductionTask reads
processDefinition via a live join, not a snapshot, so a change made in
Configuration could silently alter the rules for work already
in-progress on the shop floor mid-task, with zero warning. Same
category of risk for toggling a department off while units are
actively routed through it.

New GET /process-definitions/:id/impact and GET /departments/:id/impact
- return real counts (active tasks, affected units) computed from
actual current ProductionTask/Unit rows, not guesses. New shared
ImpactWarningModal component shows these before a risky save commits,
requiring explicit confirmation ("Yes, save anyway") rather than either
silently blocking the change or silently allowing it.

Wired into: Processes config page (editing an existing process checks
impact before saving; creating a new one skips the check - nothing
references it yet). Departments config page (deactivating checks
impact; activating never needs to, there's no risk in turning
something back on).

Also fixed a related, separately-discovered gap while building this:
the Departments page had no way to actually toggle a department
active/inactive at all - the status badge only displayed the current
state, nothing set it. This is the missing control for the Purchasing
on/off toggle built earlier in this session; without it, that feature
had no way to actually be exercised by an admin.

This is Step 1 of the larger plan discussed - generic, fully
admin-configurable workflow stages (replacing the hardcoded Planner ->
Manager -> Fabrication -> Assembly sequence) is Step 2 and genuinely
larger in scope; this piece stands alone and is safe to ship
independently of that larger rebuild.
